export const story = {"seriesId":"someone-should-have-told-me","storyId":"someone-should-have-told-me","storyKey":"someone-should-have-told-me/someone-should-have-told-me","seriesTitle":"Someone Should Have Told Me","seriesDescription":"Frankie Torres follows rules EXACTLY. So when he's put in charge of his little brother for a week, and a stray cat shows up, and the cat maybe eats all the snacks, and maybe has kittens in the closet—none of that is his fault. He has documentation.","title":"Someone Should Have Told Me","author":"Andrew","description":"Frankie Torres follows rules EXACTLY. So when he's put in charge of his little brother for a week, and a stray cat shows up, and the cat maybe eats all the snacks, and maybe has kittens in the closet—none of that is his fault. He has documentation.","ageRange":"7-10","genre":"Humor","tags":["funny","siblings","cats","responsibility","rules"],"coverImage":null,"chapters":[{"id":1,"number":1,"title":"A Cat Is Not a Friend","file":"chapter-1.md","markdown":"# A Cat Is Not a Friend\n\nI have to tell you about my week, but first you need to understand about the rules, because the rules are important. The rules are the whole point. If you don't understand the rules, you won't understand why none of this was my fault.\n\nMom put the rules on the refrigerator on Monday morning, before she left for her new important job meetings. She used the magnet from the dentist, the one shaped like a tooth. I don't like that magnet. The tooth is smiling, and teeth don't smile. Teeth are just there, doing their job, not being happy about it.\n\nThe rules said:\n\n1. Snack is on the counter. One snack each.\n2. Homework before screens.\n3. Stay inside. Backyard is okay if weather is nice.\n4. Call Mrs. Henderson if there's a real emergency.\n5. Take care of each other.\n\nI copied these into my Documentation Notebook, with the date and time. Mom saw me doing it and made the face that means she's trying not to say something. Then she said it anyway.\n\n\"Frankie, you don't have to write everything down.\"\n\n\"Yes I do,\" I said.\n\n\"It's just a list. For one week. While I'm at training.\"\n\n\"Evidence is important,\" I told her. This is something I learned from the courtroom show she watches after we go to bed, the one with the lawyer who points at people and says *I have DOCUMENTATION*. That lawyer never gets in trouble. I plan to also never get in trouble.\n\nMom kissed the top of my head and said, \"Take care of your brother,\" which was already Rule 5 so I don't know why she said it twice. Then she added, \"Mrs. Henderson will check in on you at lunch and after school. I'll call at noon. If you need ANYTHING, she's right next door.\"\n\n\"I know,\" I said.\n\n\"And I'll be home by six every night. It's just the days you're on your own.\"\n\n\"I KNOW,\" I said again, because she was acting like I hadn't been listening, which I had, very carefully, with documentation.\n\nThen she left.\n\nBean was watching me write. Bean is five, which means he can read some words but not all words, and the words he can't read he just guesses, and his guesses are always wrong but very confident.\n\n\"What's that say?\" he asked, pointing at the list.\n\n\"The rules.\"\n\n\"What's a SNACK,\" he said, but he said it like the word was suspicious.\n\n\"You know what a snack is, Bean.\"\n\n\"No, what's A snack. ONE snack.\" He held up one finger in case I didn't know what one meant. \"What is ONE snack?\"\n\nThis was actually a good question. I looked at the counter where Mom had put out: a bag of pretzels, a box of granola bars, some cheese sticks, a bag of apple slices, and the crackers that are shaped like fish but don't taste like fish, which is lying.\n\n\"I think,\" I said slowly, \"that a snack is one of these things. One bag of pretzels is one snack.\"\n\n\"One fish?\"\n\n\"No, one BAG of fish. The bag is the snack.\"\n\n\"What if the bag has a lot of fish?\"\n\n\"It's still one snack. The bag holds them together.\"\n\nBean thought about this. I could see him thinking. Bean thinking is dangerous, like a train made of questions that's about to crash into something.\n\n\"Frankie,\" he said. \"What if I open the bag. And take one fish. Is that a snack?\"\n\n\"That's... part of a snack.\"\n\n\"What if I open ALL the bags and take one thing from EACH bag?\"\n\n\"That would be—\" I stopped. That would be one pretzel, one granola bar, one cheese stick, one apple slice, and one fish cracker. None of those were a whole snack. But all together they were MORE than a snack. But each one separately was LESS than a snack. So was it one snack or five snacks or no snacks?\n\n\"I'll think about it,\" I said, which is what Mom says when she doesn't know the answer but doesn't want to admit it.\n\nThe cat showed up at 3:47 PM.\n\nI know the exact time because I wrote it down. The cat was sitting on the back porch like she'd been waiting for us specifically, like we were late for an appointment she had scheduled. She was orange, the color of those cheese crackers that get dust on your fingers, and she had eyes that were green and yellow at the same time, which shouldn't be allowed.\n\n\"KITTY,\" Bean said, in the voice he uses for things he wants to touch immediately.\n\n\"We can't touch it,\" I said. \"We don't know where it's been.\"\n\n\"It's been HERE,\" Bean said, pointing at the porch. \"Right there. I can see it.\"\n\nThis was technically true, which is the most annoying kind of true.\n\nThe cat meowed. It was a very specific meow, the kind of meow that means *I am hungry and you are going to fix that*. The cat also looked hungry. She was thin, except for her belly, which was round like she'd swallowed a softball.\n\n\"That cat eats too much,\" I said.\n\n\"That cat eats NOT ENOUGH,\" Bean said. \"She's STARVING, Frankie. Her tummy is empty. That's why it looks so big. It's full of empty.\"\n\nThat's not how stomachs work, but I didn't say that, because Bean was already opening the back door.\n\n\"BEAN. Rule 3. Stay inside.\"\n\nBean stopped. He looked at the cat. The cat looked at him. They had a whole conversation with their eyes, and I wasn't invited.\n\n\"Frankie,\" Bean said, very slowly, like he was explaining something to someone who wasn't as smart as him. \"If the cat comes INSIDE, then I can play with the cat AND stay inside. That's doing the rule BETTER.\"\n\n\"That's not—\" I started, but I couldn't finish, because it actually made sense. In a Bean way. If he was inside, with a cat, he was still inside. The rule said stay inside. It didn't say *stay inside WITHOUT a cat*.\n\n\"Also,\" Bean added, \"Rule 5 says take care of each other. The cat is each other.\"\n\n\"The cat is not each other. Each other means you and me.\"\n\n\"The cat is HERE. The cat is WITH US. The cat is EACH.\"\n\nThe cat walked inside like she owned the place. She walked right past both of us, went straight to Bean's room, and climbed into his closet. She pawed at his pile of stuffed animals, moving them around, rearranging them into a shape I didn't understand.\n\n\"She's making a nest,\" Bean said, delighted.\n\n\"She's being weird,\" I said.\n\n\"Weird is just a word for things you don't understand yet,\" Bean said, which was DEFINITELY something he heard on a TV show, but I didn't know which one.\n\nI looked out the window while Bean watched the cat be weird. Mrs. Henderson was coming home from somewhere, carrying way too many grocery bags and looking tired. Mrs. Henderson always looks a little tired, but today she looked tired AND annoyed, like someone had given her a problem she didn't ask for. She was also carrying a big bag of cat food, which was weird because Mrs. Henderson doesn't have a cat. She'd mentioned something last week about her sister trying to give her kittens, and how she absolutely did NOT want kittens, and how her sister never listens. I guess her sister won.\n\nI decided not to bother her unless it was a real emergency, which a cat definitely wasn't.\n\nThe cat stayed.\n\nThat's not exactly true. The cat stayed because Bean fed her, and Bean fed her because I didn't stop him, and I didn't stop him because... okay, here's the thing. The rules said ONE SNACK EACH. Each means every person. The cat is not a person. The cat is a cat. So when Bean gave the cat some cheese sticks, those weren't OUR snacks. Those were CAT snacks. Different category.\n\nI wrote this down in my Documentation Notebook: *3:58 PM - Cat given snacks from counter. Snacks were cat snacks, not people snacks. Cat is not a person. Rules do not apply to non-persons.*\n\nThis was good logic. This was LAWYER logic.\n\nThe problem was, the cat really liked snacks. And Bean really liked giving the cat snacks. And I went to the bathroom for TWO MINUTES, and when I came back, the cat was inside the snack drawer—THE ACTUAL DRAWER—and Bean was watching her like she was performing a magic trick.\n\n\"She opened it HERSELF,\" Bean said, like this was impressive and not terrifying.\n\nThe cat had eaten: all the granola bars (wrappers included, I think?), most of the cheese sticks, and an entire bag of apple slices (bag not included, thank goodness). The fish crackers were scattered across the kitchen floor like a crime scene.\n\n\"Bean,\" I said. \"How long was I gone.\"\n\n\"One bathroom,\" he said, which is not a unit of time.\n\nI looked at the cat. The cat looked at me. Her belly looked even more like a softball.\n\n\"I didn't give her those snacks,\" I said, mostly to myself. \"She TOOK those snacks. Taking and giving are different verbs. I didn't break any rules. The CAT broke rules, and cats can't break rules, because rules are for people, so really NO rules were broken.\"\n\nI wrote this down too. It's important to document your reasoning.\n\nWhen Mom came home, she looked almost as tired as Mrs. Henderson. She asked how it went, and Bean said, \"We have a cat now, she lives in my closet, her name is Scoops.\"\n\n\"Scoops?\" Mom said, not really listening. She was looking at her phone and taking off her shoes at the same time, which she always says we're not allowed to do.\n\n\"Because she SCOOPS up food,\" Bean explained. \"Like a digger. Diggers scoop.\"\n\n\"That's nice, honey,\" Mom said.\n\nBean looked at me. I looked at Bean. Mom had said *that's nice*, which is basically the same as *yes*, which is basically the same as *permission*.\n\n\"Told you,\" Bean whispered.\n\nI didn't say anything. I was thinking about the snack drawer, which was empty now, which Mom would definitely notice tomorrow.\n\nBut that was tomorrow's problem.\n\nTonight's problem was making sure Scoops stayed in Bean's closet and didn't eat anything else, which she didn't, because she was too full to move, which was fine, probably.\n\nWhen Mom asked how it went, I said fine, and that was true. The snack drawer situation was the cat's fault, and cats don't count.\n","narration":null},{"id":2,"number":2,"title":"An Emergency Is When Someone Is Dying","file":"chapter-2.md","markdown":"# An Emergency Is When Someone Is Dying\n\nTuesday was also fine, probably. It depends on how you define fine, and also how you define emergency, and also whether Mrs. Henderson was right about the cat, which she wasn't, but I didn't know that yet.\n\nThe problem started at breakfast.\n\n\"Where are the granola bars?\" Mom asked, looking in the snack drawer, which was empty because a cat had eaten everything in it, which was not my fault for reasons I have already explained.\n\n\"I don't know,\" I said, which was a lie, but a small one. A technical lie. Because I didn't know where the granola bars were NOW. They had been in a cat, but they had probably been processed by now, so they were somewhere ELSE, and I didn't know where. See? Technical truth.\n\n\"Frankie.\" Mom was using her I'm-not-mad-I'm-confused voice, which is actually worse than her mad voice because at least the mad voice is predictable. \"There was a whole box of granola bars in here yesterday.\"\n\n\"Scoops ate them,\" Bean said, because Bean has never met a secret he didn't want to tell.\n\n\"Who's Scoops?\"\n\n\"The cat. The one who lives in my closet. You said we could keep her.\"\n\nMom looked at me. I looked at the floor. The floor didn't look back because floors can't look, but I wished it would, so I'd have someone on my side.\n\n\"I didn't say you could keep a cat,\" Mom said slowly. \"I said 'that's nice.' To something I wasn't listening to. That's not the same as permission.\"\n\n\"It sounded like permission,\" Bean said.\n\n\"Benjamin.\"\n\nWhen Mom uses our real names, things are serious. My real name is Francis, which I don't like because it sounds like an old guy who does crossword puzzles and complains about the weather. Frankie is better. Frankie sounds like someone who has a skateboard, even if he doesn't actually have a skateboard.\n\n\"The cat is temporary,\" I said quickly. \"She's a stray. She was hungry. Rule 5 says take care of each other, and technically the cat is—\"\n\n\"The cat is not 'each other.' The cat is a CAT.\"\n\n\"That's what I said,\" I told Bean, but Bean wasn't listening. He had gone to check on Scoops, who was still in his closet, doing whatever cats do in closets. Sleeping, probably. Or plotting. It's hard to tell with cats.\n\nMom had to leave for her training, so she didn't have time to solve the cat problem. She just pointed at me and said, \"We will discuss this tonight. Don't do anything else that requires discussion.\"\n\n\"Define 'anything else,'\" I said, but she was already gone.\n\nHere's the thing about Tuesday: I had a plan. The plan was simple. I would take some of the money from the emergency jar in the kitchen, walk to the store, buy replacement snacks, and put them in the drawer before Mom got home. She would never know about the Cat Snack Incident. It would be like it never happened.\n\nBut there were problems with this plan.\n\nProblem 1: The store was four blocks away, which meant going OUTSIDE outside, not just backyard outside. Rule 3 said stay inside.\n\nProblem 2: I couldn't leave Bean alone. He's five. Five-year-olds cannot be left alone. They do things like put syrup in the DVD player or try to give the toaster a bath. Bean once tried to mail himself to Grandma. In a box. He was in the box for twenty minutes before I found him.\n\nProblem 3: I couldn't take Bean WITH me, because Rule 3 said he had to stay inside, and I wasn't sure if \"going to the store\" counted as inside or outside. Stores are inside. But you have to go OUTSIDE to get to them. It was a philosophical problem.\n\nThat's when I remembered Rule 4: Call Mrs. Henderson if there's a real emergency.\n\nI thought about this. An emergency is when someone is dying, or the house is on fire, or there's a stranger trying to get in. That's what emergencies are. Needing snacks is not an emergency.\n\nBut what if I DIDN'T get snacks? Then there would be no snacks in the drawer. And tomorrow, when Bean wanted a snack, there would be nothing to give him. He would be hungry. Hungry children can get sick. Sick children can... okay, I was reaching. But it was ALMOST an emergency. A pre-emergency. And preventing emergencies is just as important as responding to them. Probably.\n\nI called Mrs. Henderson.\n\n\"Hello?\" She sounded tired. She always sounds tired.\n\n\"Mrs. Henderson, this is Frankie. From next door.\"\n\n\"I know who you are, Frankie. Is everything okay?\"\n\n\"Yes. I mean, probably. I need to go to the store, and I was wondering if you could watch Bean for twenty minutes. It's sort of an emergency. A pre-emergency.\"\n\nThere was a long pause. I could hear something in the background—a meowing sound, but not from my house. Multiple meowing sounds.\n\n\"Frankie, I'm in the middle of a SITUATION. My sister has decided I need to take her cats. CATS. Plural. She had kittens three weeks ago—the cat, not my sister—and now Sandra wants me to take TWO of them AND the mother. And APPARENTLY there's a runt she can't find a home for, so she wants me to take THAT too. THREE CATS, Frankie. I don't even like ONE cat.\"\n\n\"That sounds hard,\" I said, because that's what you say when adults complain.\n\nThere was a pause. \"What store do you need to go to?\"\n\n\"The one on Miller Street. Four blocks.\"\n\n\"I need cat food anyway. Bring Bean over, I'll take you both. But we're going FAST, Frankie. I don't have time for browsing.\"\n\nWe walked to Mrs. Henderson's house first. She looked even more tired in person. There were cardboard boxes everywhere and a cat carrier sitting by the door, empty but waiting.\n\n\"Don't touch anything,\" she told Bean. Then to me: \"Let's go.\"\n\nThe walk to the store was quick. Mrs. Henderson walks fast for someone who's always tired. Bean had to half-jog to keep up, which he thought was a game. Mrs. Henderson bought a giant bag of cat food and some cans of something called \"kitten formula,\" muttering the whole time about runts and her sister's inability to plan ahead.\n\nI bought granola bars, cheese sticks, apple slices, and fish crackers. I used the emergency money. I would replace the emergency money later, somehow. That was a future problem.\n\nOn the walk back, Bean tried to tell Mrs. Henderson about diggers, but she was too busy complaining about litter boxes to listen.\n\n\"That your snacks?\" she asked, looking at my bag.\n\n\"Replacement snacks,\" I admitted.\n\n\"What happened to the original snacks?\"\n\n\"A cat ate them.\"\n\nMrs. Henderson stopped walking. She looked at me with an expression I couldn't read. Then she started walking again.\n\n\"I need to see this cat,\" she said.\n\nWe went back to my house. Bean led her straight to his closet like he was giving a museum tour. \"This is Scoops,\" he announced. \"She likes cheese sticks and sleeping and being orange.\"\n\nScoops was lying on her side on a pile of Bean's stuffed animals. She looked bigger than yesterday. Her softball belly was more like a basketball belly now. When she saw us, she didn't get up. She just lifted her head, meowed once, then put her head back down.\n\n\"Huh,\" said Mrs. Henderson.\n\n\"She's been drinking a lot of water,\" I said. \"I think she's thirsty.\"\n\n\"She's drinking a lot of water,\" Mrs. Henderson repeated, but in a different voice. Like the words meant something different when she said them.\n\n\"And she's heavier. I picked her up yesterday and she felt lighter. Cats must get heavier when they're full.\"\n\n\"Cats get heavier when they're full,\" Mrs. Henderson said, still in that strange voice. \"Yes. That's... one reason.\"\n\nShe looked at Scoops for a long time. Then she looked at me.\n\n\"That's not a stray,\" she said. \"That cat belongs to someone. I've seen her before. I think she's the Martinellis' cat, from over on Oak Street. They've had her for years.\"\n\nMy stomach did something uncomfortable. \"Are you sure?\"\n\n\"Pretty sure. Orange tabby, white paws, that little notch in her ear? That's their cat.\"\n\nI looked at Scoops. Scoops looked at me. She did have white paws. She did have a notch in her ear. I hadn't noticed because I'd been too busy documenting the snack situation.\n\n\"So I... stole someone's cat?\"\n\n\"I don't think you STOLE her. I think she wandered over and you fed her. But yes, technically, that cat belongs to the Martinellis, and they probably want her back.\"\n\n\"She CHOSE us,\" Bean said, his voice wobbling. \"She came to OUR house. She likes OUR closet.\"\n\n\"Cats don't get to choose,\" Mrs. Henderson said. \"Cats are property. You have to return her.\"\n\n\"Tomorrow,\" I said quickly. \"I'll return her tomorrow.\"\n\n\"Why not today?\"\n\nI didn't have a good answer for that. The real answer was: because Bean was looking at me like I was about to ruin his life, and I didn't want to be the person who ruined Bean's life. Not today. Maybe tomorrow I could be that person, but not today.\n\n\"I need to figure out where Oak Street is,\" I said, which was partly true.\n\nMrs. Henderson gave me a look that said she knew that wasn't the real reason. But she didn't argue.\n\n\"Tomorrow,\" she said. \"First thing.\"\n\n\"First thing,\" I agreed.\n\nAfter she left, Bean hugged Scoops very carefully, like she was made of something breakable.\n\n\"We're not really giving her back, right?\" he whispered.\n\n\"We have to. She's not our cat.\"\n\n\"But she FEELS like our cat.\"\n\n\"Feelings don't count,\" I said, but even as I said it, I knew that wasn't true. Feelings count. They just don't count as EVIDENCE.\n\nI wrote in my Documentation Notebook: *Tuesday 5:23 PM - Cat possibly belongs to Martinellis on Oak Street. Will return tomorrow. Decision to wait one more day was made for emotional reasons, which are not legally binding but are also not technically against any rules.*\n\nI didn't DECIDE to keep her. I decided to return her tomorrow. Those are completely different decisions.\n","narration":null},{"id":3,"number":3,"title":"Returning Is Not the Same as Getting Rid Of","file":"chapter-3.md","markdown":"# Returning Is Not the Same as Getting Rid Of\n\nWednesday was better than Tuesday, if you don't count the part where I made Bean cry, and the part where I carried a cat across the neighborhood for no reason, and the part where the cat peed in Bean's backpack. Other than those parts, it was fine.\n\nI woke up determined to do the right thing. Today was the day I would return Scoops to the Martinellis. I would be responsible. I would be mature. I would fix the problem I had technically not created but had also not prevented.\n\nThe problem was Bean.\n\nBean did not want to return Scoops. Bean had made this very clear by sleeping in front of his closet door like a human barricade, with Scoops curled up next to him, both of them looking at me like I was the villain in a movie.\n\n\"Bean,\" I said. \"We talked about this.\"\n\n\"I don't remember that conversation.\"\n\n\"It was yesterday. You were there. You said 'we're not really giving her back, right?' and I said 'we have to.'\"\n\n\"I don't remember.\"\n\nBean's memory is very selective. He can remember every single promise I've ever made him, including the time I said \"maybe\" about getting ice cream, which he has interpreted as a blood oath. But he cannot remember anything inconvenient, like bedtimes or the fact that we have to return the cat.\n\n\"The Martinellis miss her,\" I tried. \"She's THEIR cat. They've had her for years.\"\n\n\"She doesn't LIKE them. If she liked them, she would have stayed.\"\n\nThis was, unfortunately, a good point. Cats do have preferences. Maybe Scoops had left the Martinellis on purpose. Maybe she'd been unhappy. Maybe she'd seen Bean through the window and thought, \"Yes, that's my human now.\"\n\nBut probably not. Probably she was just a cat who wandered, and she'd wandered to our house by accident, and now I had to wander her back.\n\n\"Bean,\" I said. \"What if the Martinellis have a little girl? A little girl who's been crying every night because her cat is gone?\"\n\nBean's face did something complicated. \"They have a little girl?\"\n\n\"Maybe. I don't know. But what if they do? And what if she's sad? What if she can't sleep because she misses her cat?\"\n\nI was making this up. I had no idea if the Martinellis had children. But Bean is five, and five-year-olds believe everything if you say it in the right voice.\n\n\"How sad is she?\" Bean asked.\n\n\"Very sad. The saddest.\"\n\n\"Does she cry?\"\n\n\"Every night. Into her pillow.\"\n\n\"Does she have a stuffed animal to hug instead?\"\n\n\"No,\" I said, because I was committed now. \"She only had the cat. The cat was her only friend.\"\n\nThis was too much. Bean started crying—not for himself, but for the imaginary Martinelli girl. He was crying so hard that Scoops woke up and started meowing, probably because she thought something was actually wrong.\n\n\"We have to give her back,\" Bean sobbed. \"The little girl NEEDS her.\"\n\n\"Yes,\" I said. \"That's what I've been saying.\"\n\n\"But I'LL be sad.\"\n\n\"I know.\"\n\n\"Will someone make up a story about ME being sad?\"\n\n\"What?\"\n\n\"When I'm sad about the cat, will someone tell a little girl that I'M crying? So she feels bad and gives me HER cat?\"\n\nI didn't know how to answer that. Bean's logic is like a maze with no exit.\n\n\"Let's just get the cat,\" I said.\n\nGetting the cat was harder than expected.\n\nScoops did not want to leave the closet. When I tried to pick her up, she hissed at me—actually HISSED, like a snake with fur—and retreated deeper into the pile of stuffed animals.\n\n\"She's mad at you,\" Bean said, which was not helpful.\n\n\"She's a CAT. Cats don't get mad.\"\n\n\"Scoops does. She's mad because you're trying to return her. She knows.\"\n\nScoops did seem to know. Every time I reached for her, she scooted away. Her belly was even bigger today, so big that she moved slowly, like it was hard to carry. She looked exhausted just from the effort of avoiding me.\n\n\"She's tired,\" I said. \"Look at her. She's barely moving.\"\n\n\"She's resting,\" Bean said. \"For the journey.\"\n\n\"What journey?\"\n\n\"The journey HOME. To the Martinellis. She needs her strength.\"\n\nThis was surprisingly thoughtful for Bean. I almost felt bad about the whole thing. Almost.\n\nFinally, I got Scoops into Bean's backpack. It was the only bag big enough, and also the only bag Scoops didn't hiss at, probably because it smelled like Bean. I left it unzipped so she could breathe, and I carried it very carefully, like I was carrying something precious, which I was, even if I didn't want to be.\n\nI called Mrs. Henderson before we left. \"We're returning the cat to the Martinellis,\" I said. \"Can you walk us there?\"\n\nShe sighed the sigh of someone who has too many things to do and just got asked to do one more. \"Fine. But only because I want to make sure I was right about that cat. Give me two minutes.\"\n\nMrs. Henderson met us on the sidewalk. She looked at the backpack, which meowed at her.\n\n\"That's a terrible cat carrier,\" she said.\n\n\"It's the only thing that worked.\"\n\nBean walked between us, holding my hand and sniffling.\n\n\"Will she remember us?\" he asked.\n\n\"Cats don't really remember things.\"\n\n\"Scoops does. She remembered which closet was best. She remembered which drawer had snacks.\"\n\n\"That's instinct, not memory.\"\n\n\"What's instinct?\"\n\n\"It's like... knowing something without learning it.\"\n\n\"So she INSTINCTS us?\"\n\n\"That's not a verb.\"\n\n\"Everything can be a verb if you try hard enough.\"\n\nThe Martinellis lived on Oak Street, which was four blocks away in a direction I didn't usually go. Mrs. Henderson walked fast, like she always does, and Bean had to half-jog again. The houses there were bigger than ours, with gardens that looked like someone actually took care of them instead of just hoping the plants would figure it out themselves.\n\nWe found the right house by the address Mrs. Henderson remembered. It was blue with white shutters and a porch with chairs that matched. There was a garden gnome by the front steps, smiling in a way that seemed threatening.\n\nI knocked on the door.\n\nA man answered. He was older than my dad, with gray hair and glasses and a mustache that looked like it took a lot of work to maintain.\n\n\"Can I help you?\" he said.\n\n\"Are you Mr. Martinelli?\"\n\n\"I am.\"\n\n\"I think we have your cat.\" I held up the backpack, which meowed on cue.\n\nMr. Martinelli looked at the backpack. He looked at me. He looked at Bean, who was still sniffling. Then he looked back at the backpack.\n\n\"That's not my cat,\" he said.\n\nMy stomach dropped. \"What?\"\n\n\"That's not my cat. Our cat was a boy, first of all. An orange and white tabby. This cat is orange all over.\"\n\nI looked at Scoops through the gap in the backpack. She was orange all over. I had noticed she had white paws, but now that I looked more carefully, her paws were orange too. Light orange, but still orange.\n\n\"But Mrs. Henderson said—\"\n\n\"Mrs. Henderson?\" Mr. Martinelli shook his head. \"Nice lady, but she's not great with animals. She once told me my dog was sick because he was panting. In July. Dogs pant, that's what they do.\"\n\n\"So this isn't your cat?\"\n\n\"Never seen her before.\" He squinted at the backpack. \"She's pregnant, though. Very pregnant. You might want to get her checked out.\"\n\n\"She's WHAT?\"\n\nMrs. Henderson made a sound like she'd just remembered something she should have known all along. \"Oh, for crying out loud. She's not fat from snacks. She's pregnant.\"\n\n\"Pregnant. Going to have kittens. Soon, by the look of it.\" Mr. Martinelli smiled, like this was good news and not the worst news I had ever heard. \"Congratulations. You're going to be a cat grandpa.\"\n\nI didn't know what to say. I just stood there, holding a backpack full of pregnant cat that didn't belong to anyone, while Bean tugged at my sleeve and Mrs. Henderson muttered something about not needing MORE cats in the neighborhood.\n\n\"Frankie,\" he said. \"Frankie. She's not their cat.\"\n\n\"I know.\"\n\n\"That means we can KEEP her.\"\n\n\"That's not—that's not how it works.\"\n\nBut also, kind of, that WAS how it worked. If Scoops didn't belong to the Martinellis, and she didn't have a collar, and no one had put up any signs looking for her... then she was a stray. A real stray. And strays need homes. And we had a home.\n\nAnd apparently, we were about to have kittens.\n\nThe walk back was quiet. Scoops had peed in the backpack at some point, probably from the stress, and the backpack was now garbage. Bean didn't seem to care. He was too busy being excited.\n\n\"How many kittens do you think?\" he asked.\n\n\"I don't know.\"\n\n\"Can I name them?\"\n\n\"I don't know.\"\n\n\"Can I name them ALL Digger?\"\n\n\"That's confusing.\"\n\n\"Digger One, Digger Two, Digger Three—\"\n\n\"That's STILL confusing.\"\n\nMrs. Henderson walked slightly ahead of us, moving fast like she always does. When we got to her driveway, she stopped and turned around.\n\n\"I shouldn't have told you she was the Martinellis' cat without checking,\" she said. \"I was so sure. Orange tabby, white paws—except I guess her paws aren't really white, are they? They're just light orange. I need new glasses.\"\n\n\"It's okay,\" I said.\n\n\"It's NOT okay. Now you've got a pregnant stray and I've got three cats from my sister including a runt that won't eat right and probably needs bottle feeding every two hours, which I absolutely do not have time for.\" She sighed. \"I'm sixty-three years old and I'm becoming a cat lady against my will.\"\n\n\"That sounds hard,\" I said, because what else do you say?\n\nShe looked at me for a long moment. \"You don't want a kitten, do you? Once yours are born? Save me from having to find homes for four more cats?\"\n\n\"No,\" I said automatically. \"I don't think—my mom wouldn't—\"\n\n\"Fair enough.\" She went inside, still muttering about litter boxes and sisters who don't listen.\n\nBean was quiet until we got home. Then he looked at me with the most serious expression I'd ever seen on his face.\n\n\"Frankie.\"\n\n\"What?\"\n\n\"Kittens are like tiny cats, right?\"\n\n\"Yes.\"\n\n\"And tiny cats are like tiny diggers?\"\n\n\"No. That doesn't make sense.\"\n\n\"Everything makes sense if you think about it right,\" Bean said, which is the most Bean thing anyone has ever said.\n\nI put Scoops back in Bean's closet. She seemed relieved, curling up immediately in her nest of stuffed animals. Her belly rose and fell with her breathing. Inside that belly were kittens. Real kittens. Kittens that I hadn't asked for and didn't know how to take care of.\n\nI wrote in my Documentation Notebook: *Wednesday 4:47 PM - Cat is NOT Martinellis' cat. Cat belongs to no one. Cat is also pregnant. This is not something I planned. This is not something I asked for. This is happening anyway.*\n\n*Note: Mrs. Henderson has a runt kitten she can't take care of. This is not relevant to my situation. I'm just writing it down because it happened.*\n\nI didn't know why I wrote that last part. It just seemed important.\n","narration":null},{"id":4,"number":4,"title":"Responsible People Ask For Help","file":"chapter-4.md","markdown":"# Responsible People Ask For Help\n\nThursday was the day I learned that being scared and being responsible are not opposites. Sometimes they're the same thing.\n\nIt started at 3 AM.\n\nI know it was 3 AM because I was already awake, lying in bed and thinking about all the things that could go wrong with a pregnant cat, when I heard the sound. It was a yowl—not a normal cat sound, but something deeper and stranger, like Scoops was trying to say something important but didn't have the words.\n\nI got up and went to Bean's room. Bean was still asleep, because Bean can sleep through anything. Once he slept through a fire alarm test that lasted eleven minutes. He just rolled over and dreamed about diggers.\n\nScoops was in her closet nest, but she was lying differently than before. She was stretched out on her side with her paws extended, and her breathing was fast. Her belly looked even bigger, if that was possible—not round anymore but lumpy, like there were things moving around inside it.\n\n\"Scoops?\" I whispered.\n\nShe looked at me. Just looked. And in that look was something I hadn't seen before: she was scared too.\n\nI didn't know what to do. I'd never had a pet. The closest thing was the class hamster in second grade, and Mr. Whiskers had been very healthy and very boring and had never done anything except run on his wheel and eat pellets. He definitely never had babies in anyone's closet.\n\nI went back to bed, but I didn't sleep. I just lay there, listening for more yowling, trying to remember if Mom had said anything about what to do if your secret pregnant cat started acting strange.\n\nShe hadn't. Because Mom didn't know about the secret pregnant cat. Because I hadn't told her.\n\nIn the morning, things were worse.\n\nScoops wouldn't eat. I put a bowl of food right next to her nest, and she just sniffed it and turned away. She was drinking water, a lot of water, but she wouldn't touch the food. Her eyes were half-closed and she kept making a low humming sound, like a machine that wasn't working right.\n\n\"Is she broken?\" Bean asked, standing in the doorway of his closet.\n\n\"Cats don't break.\"\n\n\"She looks broken. She looks like when the TV gets stuck and we have to turn it off and on again.\"\n\n\"You can't turn a cat off and on again.\"\n\n\"Why not?\"\n\n\"Because that's not how cats work, Bean.\"\n\nBut I understood what he meant. Something was wrong with Scoops, and I didn't know how to fix it.\n\nI thought about Rule 4. *Call Mrs. Henderson if there's a real emergency.*\n\nWas this a real emergency? Scoops wasn't dying. Probably. I didn't actually know what dying looked like in cats. Maybe this WAS dying. Maybe pregnant cats always acted like this before they died. Maybe I was watching a cat die and I didn't even know it.\n\nThe thought made my stomach hurt.\n\nBut calling Mrs. Henderson meant telling her that I still had the cat. That I'd had the cat all week. That I knew she was pregnant now and I hadn't done anything about it. That I'd been lying, sort of, about the whole situation.\n\nI went back through the rules in my head:\n\nRule 1: No friends over without asking. ✓ (The cat is not a friend.)\nRule 2: Bean must stay inside until Mom gets home. ✓ (Bean has been inside.)\nRule 3: Snacks only from the approved snack drawer. ✓ (I replaced the snacks.)\nRule 4: Call Mrs. Henderson if there's a real emergency. ??? (Is this an emergency?)\nRule 5: Take care of each other. ✓ (I've been taking care of Bean.)\n\nI had followed all the rules. Every single one. I had documentation to prove it.\n\nSo why did I feel like I had done something wrong?\n\nI sat on Bean's bed, looking at Scoops, and I realized something. The rules weren't really about the rules. The rules were about making good choices. About being responsible. About thinking ahead and not doing stupid things that caused problems.\n\nAnd I had done a stupid thing that caused problems. I had kept a pregnant cat in a closet for a week and pretended everything was fine.\n\nThe rules said I was okay. But the rules were wrong. Or I was using them wrong. Or something.\n\nI picked up the phone and called Mrs. Henderson.\n\n\"Hello?\" She sounded tired. She always sounds tired. But this time I understood why.\n\n\"Mrs. Henderson, it's Frankie. I need help.\"\n\nThere was a pause. \"What kind of help?\"\n\n\"The cat. Scoops. She's acting strange. She won't eat and she's making noises and she looks... she looks scared. And I don't know what to do. And I know I should have told you sooner. And I know I should have done a lot of things differently. But right now I just need someone who knows about cats because I don't know about cats and something is wrong and I'm scared too.\"\n\nIt all came out in one breath, like a dam breaking.\n\nMrs. Henderson was quiet for a long time. Then she said, \"I'll be right over.\"\n\nWhen she got there, she didn't yell at me. She didn't lecture me about responsibility or make me feel stupid. She just went straight to Bean's closet and looked at Scoops.\n\n\"Oh, honey,\" she said, but she was talking to the cat, not to me. \"You're almost there, aren't you?\"\n\n\"Almost WHERE?\" I asked.\n\nMrs. Henderson looked at me. Her face did something complicated—a little bit of frustration, a little bit of sympathy, a lot of tiredness.\n\n\"Frankie, this cat is going to have kittens. Tonight, probably. Maybe tomorrow morning if we're lucky. She's in labor.\"\n\n\"Labor like... working hard?\"\n\n\"Labor like giving birth. Her body is getting ready to push out the kittens. That's why she's acting strange. That's why she won't eat. That's why she's making noises. This is what cats do right before they become mothers.\"\n\nI looked at Scoops. Scoops looked at me. Inside her belly, kittens were getting ready to exist.\n\n\"What do I do?\" I asked.\n\n\"Well.\" Mrs. Henderson sighed. \"Ideally, you would have taken her to a vet days ago. But we're past that now. So we make do.\"\n\nShe sent me to get old towels from the linen closet. She had Bean bring his stuffed animals to his bed so Scoops would have more room. She arranged the towels into a proper nest, with walls on the sides so the kittens wouldn't roll away.\n\n\"Keep her warm,\" she said. \"Keep her calm. Don't pick her up or move her around. Let her do what she needs to do. Cats have been having kittens for thousands of years without help—she'll figure it out. But if something goes wrong—if she's in labor for more than a few hours without any kittens, or if a kitten comes out but doesn't move, or if there's a lot of blood—you call me immediately. Got it?\"\n\n\"Got it.\"\n\nShe stood up, groaning a little. \"This is the most irresponsible responsible thing I've ever seen, you know that?\"\n\n\"What does that mean?\"\n\n\"It means you did everything wrong AND everything right at the same time. You kept a cat without permission, you didn't tell anyone she was pregnant, you tried to return her to the wrong people, and you waited until the last minute to ask for help.\" She paused. \"But you also fed her, and you kept her safe, and you made sure she had a warm place to rest, and when things got scary, you called someone instead of pretending everything was fine. That last part is the important part.\"\n\nI didn't know what to say. I felt like crying, but I wasn't sure if they were good tears or bad tears.\n\n\"Thank you for coming,\" I managed.\n\n\"Of course I came. You asked.\" She looked at me with an expression I couldn't quite read. \"You know, my sister's runt kitten—the one I mentioned? She's so small. Needs someone to feed her every two hours, or she won't make it. Needs someone who pays attention. Someone who takes things seriously.\" She paused. \"Even if they take them seriously in the wrong direction.\"\n\n\"I don't—\"\n\n\"I'm not saying anything. Just thinking out loud.\" She patted my shoulder. \"Call me if you need anything. Even if it's 3 AM. Even if it's not a 'real emergency.' Sometimes the non-emergencies are the important ones.\"\n\nAfter she left, I sat outside Bean's closet. Bean had fallen asleep on his bed, surrounded by stuffed animals, still wearing his shoes because he'd forgotten to take them off. Scoops was breathing steadily, her eyes closed, her body working on something I couldn't see.\n\nI opened my Documentation Notebook and started writing.\n\n*Thursday 4:15 PM - Called Mrs. Henderson for help. This was not because of Rule 4. Rule 4 says to call for emergencies. This was not an emergency (probably). I called because I was scared and I didn't know what to do and I needed someone to tell me it would be okay.*\n\n*Note: I should have noticed the cat was pregnant. The signs were there. The big belly. The nesting. The water drinking. Mr. Martinelli noticed right away. Mrs. Henderson noticed right away. I didn't notice because I was too busy thinking about rules.*\n\n*Second note: Rules are not the same as doing the right thing. They can overlap. But they're not the same.*\n\nI kept writing. I wrote down everything I should have noticed and didn't. Every sign I'd missed. Every moment where I'd convinced myself that following the rules meant I was being responsible, when really I was just avoiding the harder thing, which was admitting I didn't know what I was doing.\n\nThe list was very long.\n\nBy the time I finished, it was dark outside. Bean was still asleep. Scoops was still breathing. And I was still scared.\n\nBut at least I had asked for help. That had to count for something.\n\nI didn't sleep. I sat outside Bean's closet with my Documentation Notebook and a flashlight, listening to Scoops breathe, waiting for whatever was going to happen next.\n\nI was going to be a terrible lawyer.\n\nBut maybe that was okay.\n","narration":null},{"id":5,"number":5,"title":"Take Care of Each Other","file":"chapter-5.md","markdown":"# Take Care of Each Other\n\nI have had better weeks.\n\nBut I have also had worse weeks, like the week Derek Kozlowski told everyone I ate a worm when I only HELD a worm, and also the week I had the flu and threw up in the car, and also the week Grandma's parrot learned to say my name in an angry voice, which still gives me nightmares.\n\nThis week was different. This week I followed every rule on the refrigerator and still ended up with five cats in my brother's closet.\n\nIt happened like this:\n\nI woke up because someone was shaking me. I hadn't meant to fall asleep—I was supposed to be watching Scoops—but at some point my eyes had closed and the next thing I knew, Bean was standing over me with the biggest smile I had ever seen on his face.\n\n\"FRANKIE,\" he said. \"FRANKIE. THERE'S TINY CATS.\"\n\nFor a second I didn't understand. Then I remembered where I was and what I was supposed to be watching, and I scrambled to the closet so fast I tripped over my own Documentation Notebook.\n\nScoops was lying on her side in the nest of towels. She looked exhausted, like she had just run a marathon or taken a very hard test. But she also looked proud, in the way that cats look proud, which is basically how they always look but more so.\n\nAnd next to her, curled up against her belly, were four kittens.\n\nThey were tiny. So tiny. The biggest one was the size of my hand, and the smallest one was the size of my hand if I made a fist. They were wet and wriggly and their eyes were closed and they were making tiny squeaking sounds that didn't sound like cats at all. They sounded like questions.\n\n\"They're so SMALL,\" Bean whispered, like he was in church or at the library.\n\n\"They just got born. They'll get bigger.\"\n\n\"Are they diggers?\"\n\n\"They're CATS, Bean.\"\n\n\"Tiny cats.\"\n\n\"Yes.\"\n\n\"Tiny cats that I get to NAME.\"\n\nI was too overwhelmed to argue. Four kittens. Scoops had four kittens in Bean's closet while I was sleeping, and now there were five cats in our house instead of one, and Mom was going to be home in eight hours, and I had no idea what I was going to say.\n\nActually, that's not true. I knew exactly what I was going to say. I had practiced it in my head all night, between naps. I was going to explain everything, rule by rule, decision by decision, and show Mom that even though things had gotten a little out of control, I had technically followed all the rules and therefore couldn't be blamed.\n\nIt was a good plan. A lawyer plan.\n\nI just wasn't sure it was the right plan anymore.\n\n---\n\nMom came home at 5:30, earlier than usual, because her training had ended early and she wanted to \"check in on how things were going.\"\n\nThings were going... complicated.\n\n\"Frankie?\" Mom called from the front door. \"Bean? How was your—\"\n\nShe stopped. Because Bean was standing in the hallway holding a kitten, and the kitten was mewing, and behind Bean I was standing with an expression that probably looked like someone who had done something they needed to explain but didn't know how to start.\n\n\"What,\" Mom said, very slowly, \"is that?\"\n\n\"A baby tiny cat,\" Bean said. \"Her name is Digger. I have three more. They're all named Digger.\"\n\nMom looked at the kitten. She looked at Bean. She looked at me.\n\n\"Frankie. Explain.\"\n\nSo I did.\n\nI told her about Monday, and the cat showing up, and how I'd decided she wasn't technically a friend so Rule 1 didn't apply. I told her about the snack drawer and how I'd replaced everything so she wouldn't notice. I told her about Mrs. Henderson thinking the cat belonged to the Martinellis, and the trip to Oak Street, and Mr. Martinelli saying it wasn't his cat. I told her about calling Mrs. Henderson when I got scared, and how she'd said the cat was in labor, and how I'd stayed up all night waiting.\n\nI told her everything, in order, with documentation.\n\nWhen I finished, Mom was sitting on Bean's bed. She hadn't said a word the whole time. The quiet was worse than yelling. The quiet was the worst thing.\n\nFinally, she spoke.\n\n\"Frankie. Do you understand why I'm upset?\"\n\n\"Because I didn't tell you about the cat?\"\n\n\"That's part of it.\"\n\n\"Because there are five cats in Bean's closet now?\"\n\n\"That's also part of it.\"\n\n\"Because I used emergency money to buy replacement snacks?\"\n\n\"I didn't even know about that part, but yes, add it to the list.\" Mom rubbed her face with her hands. \"Frankie. The rules were not a puzzle to solve. They weren't a game where you find loopholes and technically-this and technically-that. They were supposed to help you make good decisions.\"\n\n\"I DID make good decisions,\" I said. \"I made the BEST decisions. I documented everything. I followed the rules exactly. I—\"\n\n\"You hid a pregnant cat from me for a week.\"\n\n\"But I—\"\n\n\"You let your five-year-old brother feed her snacks until she ate everything in the drawer.\"\n\n\"That was—\"\n\n\"You tried to return her to strangers without even checking if she was really their cat.\"\n\n\"Mrs. Henderson said—\"\n\n\"And you didn't tell me ANY of this until right now, when you're standing in front of me with a closet full of kittens.\"\n\nI didn't have a response to that. Because she was right. I had done all of those things. They just didn't feel wrong when I was doing them because the rules said I was okay.\n\nBut the rules weren't really okay. I just wanted them to be.\n\n\"I'm sorry,\" I said, and I meant it. \"I thought if I followed the rules, nothing could go wrong. And then things kept going wrong anyway, and I didn't know how to fix it, so I just... kept following the rules.\"\n\nMom looked at me for a long time. Then she sighed—not an angry sigh, just a tired one.\n\n\"What are we going to do with five cats?\"\n\nI didn't have an answer.\n\n---\n\nMrs. Henderson knocked on the door twenty minutes later.\n\nShe was carrying a cat carrier, and inside the carrier was a very small orange kitten—much smaller than any of Scoops' kittens, small enough to fit in a teacup.\n\n\"The runt,\" she said, when Mom opened the door. \"My sister's cat had five kittens three weeks ago, and this one isn't thriving. Vet says she needs bottle feeding every two hours, lots of attention, someone who can really focus on her. I'm too old for that. I was going to take her to the shelter, see if they could help, but...\" She looked past Mom, at me. \"But then I thought about Frankie.\"\n\n\"Me?\" I said.\n\n\"You've been taking care of that cat all week. Even when you shouldn't have been. Even when it made no sense. Even when it meant bending every rule in your little notebook.\" She held up the carrier. \"This kitten needs someone who takes things too seriously. Someone who writes everything down. Someone who won't give up just because things get hard.\"\n\nI stared at the kitten. She was so small. Her eyes weren't even open yet. She was mewing, a tiny sound that was barely louder than breathing.\n\n\"Mrs. Henderson,\" Mom said carefully, \"I'm not sure this is the best time—\"\n\n\"It's exactly the right time.\" Mrs. Henderson looked at Mom. \"Your son made a lot of mistakes this week. But he also did something right: when things got scary, he asked for help. He didn't pretend everything was fine. He admitted he didn't know what to do.\" She paused. \"That's harder than following rules. That's the thing that actually matters.\"\n\nMom looked at me. I looked at Mom. The kitten mewed.\n\n\"This is not a reward,\" Mom said finally. \"Do you understand that, Frankie? If we take this kitten—and I'm not saying we ARE, but IF—it's not because you did a good job this week. It's because the kitten needs help and you might be able to give it.\"\n\n\"I understand.\"\n\n\"You'll have to feed her every two hours. That means setting alarms. That means waking up at night. That means actually being responsible, not just technically responsible.\"\n\n\"I know.\"\n\n\"And the other cats—Scoops and her kittens—we'll need to find homes for them. We can't keep five cats, Frankie. We just can't.\"\n\n\"I know,\" I said again. But I was looking at the runt in the carrier, and she was looking at me—except she couldn't actually look at me because her eyes were closed, but it felt like looking anyway. It felt like she was asking me something.\n\n\"I'll do it,\" I said. \"I'll take care of her. Really take care of her. Not because the rules say I can, but because she needs me.\"\n\nMom was quiet for a long moment. Then she nodded.\n\n\"Okay. But I'm holding you to that.\"\n\nMrs. Henderson handed me the carrier. The kitten inside was warm, even through the plastic. She squeaked when I took her, like she knew something important was happening.\n\n\"What are you going to name her?\" Bean asked, crowding close to look.\n\nI thought about it. The whole week, Bean had named everything—the cat, the kittens, probably some of the stuffed animals. But this one felt different. This one was mine.\n\n\"Actually,\" I said, \"you can name her.\"\n\nBean's face lit up. \"Really?\"\n\n\"Really.\"\n\nHe thought about it very seriously, the way he thinks about important things, like which flavor of ice cream is best (chocolate, always chocolate) and whether dinosaurs or diggers would win in a fight (diggers, because they have shovels).\n\n\"Peanut,\" he said finally. \"Because she's small like a peanut.\"\n\n\"Peanut,\" I repeated. It was a good name. A small name for a small cat.\n\n\"That's a good name,\" Mrs. Henderson said.\n\n\"Bean is good at names,\" I admitted.\n\n---\n\nThat night, after Mom had called three of her friends about taking kittens, and after Mrs. Henderson had gone home, and after Bean had finally fallen asleep surrounded by stuffed animals and exactly zero cats (Scoops and the kittens were in a proper box now, in the corner of my room where I could watch them), I did something.\n\nI went to the refrigerator. I found a pen. And under the five rules Mom had written, I added a sixth:\n\n*Rule 6: Sometimes the rules don't cover everything. Sometimes you have to figure it out yourself.*\n\nIn the morning, Mom saw it. I watched her from the kitchen doorway, nervous, waiting for her to be angry.\n\nShe wasn't angry. She read it twice, and then she laughed—a real laugh, not a tired one.\n\n\"You're going to be a lawyer someday,\" she said. \"God help us all.\"\n\n\"Mrs. Henderson said the same thing.\"\n\n\"Mrs. Henderson is a wise woman.\" Mom looked at me. \"Keep that rule. It's a good one.\"\n\n---\n\nPeanut slept in my room that first night, in a box with a heating pad and a towel that smelled like my sweater. I set my alarm for every two hours, just like the vet had said. At 2 AM, I fed her with a tiny bottle, and she drank so much that her belly got round like a marble. At 4 AM, I fed her again, and she fell asleep in my hand before she was even done.\n\nBean wanted to help, but he's five, and five-year-olds need their sleep.\n\n\"I'll do it,\" I told him. \"I'm in charge.\"\n\nAnd this time, I actually was.\n\n---\n\n*Final entry in the Documentation Notebook:*\n\n*This week I learned that following rules is not the same as doing the right thing. Sometimes they overlap. But sometimes you have to do the right thing even when there's no rule for it. And sometimes you have to ask for help, even when you're scared, even when it means admitting you don't know what you're doing.*\n\n*Also I learned that cats can have kittens in closets, and that kittens are very small, and that small things need people who take them seriously.*\n\n*Mrs. Henderson's runt kitten is called Peanut. She is mine now. She fits in one hand. She has to eat every two hours.*\n\n*I'm tired.*\n\n*But I'm also responsible.*\n\n*The real kind.*\n","narration":null}],"chapterCount":5,"audio":null,"narration":{"hasNarration":false,"chapters":[]},"assets":[],"standalone":false};
